and refusal to compromise, the meaning and limits of political integrity, representation and failures of representation, good and bad democratic leadership, the virtues and excesses of partisanship, administrative ethics, political corruption, whistleblowing, legitimate and illegitimate claims of political emergency, and lobbying. What emerges are realistic but demanding ethical standards—and a clear-eyed understanding of the ethical challenges of political life in the twenty-first century.With contributions by Richard Bellamy, Alin Fumurescu, Edward Hall, Suzanne Dovi and Jesse McCain, Eric Beerbohm, Russell Muirhead and Nancy Rosenblum, Joseph Heath, Elizabeth David-Barrett and Mark Philp, Michele Bocchiola and Emanuela Ceva, Nomi Lazar, Phil Parvin, and Andrew Sabl.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aPolitical ethics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aA Critique of Pure Tolerance.  aAbuse of power.  aAccountability.  aActivism.  aAttempt.  aAuthoritarianism.  aBig lie.  aBribery.  aBully pulpit.  aBusiness ethics.  aCensure.  aCitizens (Spanish political party).  aCivil disobedience.  aCivil service.  aClassified information.  aClimate change denial.  aCommon good.  aConsequentialism.  aConsideration.  aConspiracy theory.  aCorruption.  aCrisis management.  aCronyism.  aCruel and unusual punishment.  aDecisionism.  aDeliberation.  aDemagogue.  aDenunciation.  aDeontological ethics.  aDespotism.  aDictatorship.  aDirty hands.  aDisparagement.  aElectoral fraud.  aElitism.  aEthical dilemma.  aEthics.  aExternality.  aFraud.  aFreedom of speech.  aGood and evil.  aGovernance.  aHomo sacer.  aImpasse.  aImpose.  aImpunity.  aIndividual and group rights.  aIndividualism.  aInformation asymmetry.  aInjunction.  aInstitu